Children's sharp observation establishes the true connection between the mother's increasing stoutness during pregnancy and the appearance of the baby. This precocious discovery is always kept secret and later repressed and forgotten in conformity with the vicissitudes of sexual researches.
Children's false sexual theories, though going astray in grotesque fashion, each contain a fragment of real truth
Hans's case confirms in the most concrete and uncompromising manner what was said about the sexual relations of a child to his parents

The emotional life of man is in general made up of pairs of contraries. The child deeply loves the father against whom he cherishes death-wishes. This contradiction does not prevent both feelings from existing simultaneously.

In the adult, pairs of contrary emotions do not usually become simultaneously conscious except at the climaxes of passionate love. In children, contradictory feelings can persist for long periods side by side in conscious form.

The language of obsessional neurosis is a dialect of the language of hysteria, more nearly related to conscious thought forms than hysteria and not involving the leap to somatic innervation (hysterical conversion) which can never be fully comprehensible.

In obsessional neurosis, if the patient can be induced to give a particular instance in place of vague generalities, it may be confidently assumed that the instance is the original and actual thing which has tried to hide itself behind the generalization.

The child's elementary obsessional neurosis at six or seven years was not merely the beginning of the illness but was already the complete illness itself - wanting in no essential element, serving as both nucleus and prototype of the later disorder.

The inventory of obsessional neurosis includes: an erotic instinct and a revolt against it; a wish which has not yet become compulsive; a fear which is already compulsive; a distressing affect; and an impulsion towards defensive acts.

The child's idea 'I speak my thoughts out loud without hearing them' represents an endopsychic perception of what has been repressed - a projection into the external world of the hypothesis that he had thoughts without knowing anything about them.

Modern civilization requires an extraordinary amount of sexual repression, which depletes the energy available for civilized activity and creates widespread nervous illness. The cost of civilization may exceed its benefits when the repression becomes excessive.

Sexual morality as defined by civilized society demands renunciation of sexuality except in marriage, but this 'civilized' sexual morality injures health and achievement, creating a class of people who cannot enjoy what they have and must give up what they want, leading to nervous illness.

Marriage under civilized sexual morality fails to provide satisfactory sexual outlet, particularly for women. The prescribed abstinence before marriage weakens capacity for sexual satisfaction, while monogamous marriage soon becomes unsatisfying for men, creating conditions for neurosis.

Hysterical symptoms are the expression of unconscious phantasies which serve as psychical fulfillments of sexual wishes. These phantasies have in every case a bisexual character and represent both a masculine and a feminine unconscious sexual phantasy.

A hysterical symptom is the expression of both a masculine and a feminine unconscious sexual phantasy. An attack can represent both coitus from the man's point of view and from the woman's point of view simultaneously.

As the child grows and becomes acquainted with social differences, he gives up his exaggerated idea of his parents and creates 'family romances' - phantasies in which he imagines being a foundling or adopted child whose real parents are of higher social standing
Hysterical patients suffer from reminiscences. Their symptoms are residues and mnemic symbols of particular traumatic experiences.
Every single hysteric and neurotic remembers painful experiences of the remote past and still clings to them emotionally, unable to get free of the past

Hysterical symptoms can be likened to mnemic monuments, but where normal persons move on from commemorating the past, neurotics remain emotionally fixated to it, behaving like a Londoner who pauses in melancholy before monuments to the past instead of engaging with present life.

The processes of artistic creation are essentially parallel to neurotic symptom formation. The artist finds a way back from phantasy to reality through utilizing special gifts to mold phantasies into a new kind of reality acknowledged by others as valuable reflections of actuality.

The psycho-analyst assumes the unity and conformity to law of mental phenomena. For him there is no such thing as mere chance in mental life. He sees a strict determination that extends to seemingly arbitrary and insignificant details.

Sublimation is a process whereby the energy of infantile sexual wishful impulses is not blocked off by repression but diverted towards higher aims, no longer sexual. The ability to sublimate rather than repress infantile sexuality is a prerequisite for great cultural achievement.

Scientific research can itself become a sexual activity when the curiosity that drives it was originally attached to sexual problems in childhood. The intellectual interest in these problems can then become displaced onto other objects, providing the energy and compulsive quality to research.

A special type of object-choice in men requires two conditions: the injured third party (another man must have a rightful claim to the woman) and the loose woman (the woman must be sexually somewhat suspect and of bad reputation)

Men of this type show a compulsion to rescue the woman they love, particularly from moral or social danger. This represents the phantasy of rescuing the mother from the father's sexual activity, transforming it into the idea of giving the mother a child or making one for her.
The universal tendency to debasement in the sphere of love results from the difficulty of uniting affectionate and sensual currents
Psychical impotence affects civilized men far more than would be supposed and represents a partial failure to unite affectionate and sensual currents

Anyone who is to be really free and happy in love must have surmounted his respect for women and have come to terms with the idea of incest with his mother or sister. The barriers against incest represent the greatest sacrifice civilization demands from sexuality.
The taboo of virginity in many primitive peoples reflects the danger that the man who first ruptures the hymen will be subject to the woman's hostile reaction and vengeance

The tendency of dream-work to disregard negation and express contraries by the same element corresponds to peculiarities of the oldest languages, where many primal words possessed antithetical meanings. This confirms that the language of dreams has archaic characteristics.

Sexual enlightenment of children should not be artificially delayed or falsified. The refusal to give children information or giving them false information (stork theory) creates harmful psychical conflicts, distrust of adults, and the conditions for neurotic nuclear complex formation.

Psycho-analysis in legal proceedings can help establish facts by detecting hidden emotional reactions through word-association experiments, but its use is limited because it cannot compel the accused to participate and because neurotic symptoms (which it can interpret) differ from deceptive behavior in normal persons

If the patient can recollect the traumatic scene in hypnosis and abreact the affect that was strangulated at the time, the symptom disappears. The mechanism is that reminiscences which have become pathogenic preserve their affective charge because the reaction to them was suppressed.

The fading of a memory depends on whether there has been an energetic reaction to the event that provokes an affect. 'Reaction' includes the whole class of voluntary and involuntary reflexes by which affects are discharged - from tears to acts of revenge.

When reaction to a traumatic event is suppressed, the affect remains attached to the memory. For hysterics, the memory of trauma has not been worn away because it is denied normal wearing-away processes - it remains like a foreign body, a cause of permanent pathogenic action.

Repression creates a gap in the patient's memory, a blank space, which the patient tries to fill with invented links. The pressure technique can recover the repressed memories by forcing their way into consciousness despite resistance.

Resistance to remembering traumatic material is proportional to the distance in time from the trauma and to the importance of the memory. The stronger the resistance, the greater the distortion between repressed thought and conscious substitute.

The same force that now as resistance opposes the forgotten material's emergence into consciousness must formerly have brought about the forgetting and pushed the pathogenic experiences out of consciousness. This mechanism is repression, which is the foundation-stone of psychoanalysis.

The content that caused the defense leading to illness was always of a sexual nature, involving conflict between sexual idea and patient's moral and aesthetic standards. The patient's sexuality was incompatible with the whole complex of other ideas ruling in his mind.

Sexual instinct in man does not serve reproduction's purposes alone but seeks to gain particular kinds of pleasure. It manifests itself as a force (libido) which is able to displace its aim (to sublimate) without materially losing intensity.

Children are capable of every psychical sexual activity and many somatic ones from the beginning. Perverse sexuality is infantile sexuality, magnified and dissected into its separate impulses. Perversions are either inhibitions of development or dissociations of it.
The sexual function begins at the start of life, immediately after birth, though it passes through complicated development

A child's sexual life is put under prohibition and repression, but some part of it escapes this fate and manifests itself as non-sexual activity (sublimation) or continues until sexual maturity but in repressed form, constituting the unconscious sexual life of the person.

Neurotic symptoms are substitute satisfactions for unsatisfied sexual desires. Symptoms mean the same thing in all cases: they are a substitute for an inct satisfaction and are sustained by the same libidinal forces seeking satisfaction (wishful impulses).
The unconscious is not just the latest repressed but includes mental acts that are latent and temporarily unconscious

The interpretation of dreams is the royal road to knowledge of the unconscious in mental life. Dreams are constructed like symptoms, representing wish-fulfillments of unconscious wishful impulses that have escaped repression.
Transference develops in every psychoanalytic treatment without physician intervention
Psychoanalytic therapy's task is to make conscious what is pathogenically unconscious

The delay of puberty in intellectually precocious children determines whether later sexual development will be normal, perverse, or lead to neurosis. When puberty is delayed, intellectual curiosity can connect with sublimated sexuality, giving thought itself the quality of a sexual process.

Three possible outcomes from infantile sexual investigation: neurotic inhibition (thought remains sexualized and inhibited), obsessive brooding (intellectual activity becomes sexualized, returning as brooding), or sublimation (libido escapes repression by sublimating from beginning into curiosity for science)
The absence of the father in Leonardo's early childhood combined with exceptionally strong attachment to his mother determined his homosexual orientation
Homosexuality results from particularly intense erotic attachment to the mother in the first years of life, later forgotten
Artistic talent and capacity for work are intimately connected with sublimation

The phobia serves the purpose of inhibiting motility, the expression of aggressive impulse. Though appearing as a restriction of the ego, phobia is actually an attempt at flight from instinctual demand. The patient acquires a neurotic illness to escape an apparently unsolvable task.
The child's knowledge is different in kind before and after sexual enlightenment

The castration complex is the deepest unconscious root of anti-semitism, as circumcision unconsciously equates to castration. This produces the uncanny effect and reminds the non-Jew of his own castration threat in childhood.
In obsessional neurosis, the sadistic-anal organization of sexual life is particularly important

The obsessional neurotic's uncertainty and doubt is expression of inner battle between love and hate for same person. The doubt spreads from original sexual conflict to all else. Obsessive measures are attempts at resolution but never succeed, creating the characteristic indecision.

Obsessional neurotics suffer from omnipotence of thoughts - they believe their hostile wishes have real power. This over-valuation of psychical acts and magical thinking is remnant of narcissistic phase of development, similar to animistic phase of mankind.

The sexual instinct in neurotics has not advanced to final normal shape but remained arrested at or returned to earlier phase. Clinical types of neurosis (hysteria, obsessional neurosis) correspond to fixation at particular stages of libidinal development.

Obsessional neurosis shows fixation at sadistic-anal stage of libidinal organization, with exaggerated anal erotism and aggressive sadistic impulses toward love-objects. When regression to this stage occurs, ambivalence and omnipotence of thoughts emerge as dominant features.

In the delusion, repressed material returns in distorted form through the very thing chosen as instrument of repression. The archaeologist's interest in antiquities becomes the vehicle through which the repressed childhood love returns, demonstrating that repressed proves itself victor in the end.

The technique of psychoanalytic therapy for delusions consists in revealing the repressed material behind them. Once the repressed is made conscious, patients themselves bring forward solutions to final riddles of their condition in sudden ideas, tearing the last threads of delusion themselves.

Dreams created by imaginative writers can be interpreted using same principles as real dreams. The poet draws upon same sources of unconscious material as the dreamer, with creative writing representing controlled use of primary process mechanisms.

The first childish sexual theory is that everyone possesses a penis like the boy's own (phallic phase). When the boy sees a girl's genitals, he first denies evidence of his eyes, then perceives it as a temporary state or as result of castration, arousing castration complex.

The second sexual theory is the cloaca theory - that babies are born through the anus like a piece of faeces. This derives from the child's actual experience with anal zone and represents backwards displacement from genital to anal.

The third sexual theory is the sadistic conception of coitus. When the child observes parental intercourse, it inevitably regards it as act of subjugation, as a sadomasochistic struggle. This perception leaves lasting impression and becomes permanent component of psychosexual constitution.
The linkage between faeces, gift, baby, and penis in unconscious is demonstrated through psychoanalytic investigation

Hysterical attacks are not convulsions but represent dramatized phantasies translated into motor activity, projected onto motility, and pantomimically represented. They are substitute for auto-erotic satisfaction formerly practiced and then repressed.

The hysterical attack corresponds to coitus - either one in memory, or one that has been phantasied. It can represent both male and female parts in coitus, or may represent situation not directly sexual but libidinally colored (e.g., scene of violence, giving birth).

Hysterical attacks occur more readily when libido is dammed up and cannot be discharged through normal sexual activity. When reality provides no sexual satisfaction, libido regresses to older phantasies and actualizes them in attacks. The attack is substitute for satisfaction.

The requirement of civilized sexual morality - complete abstinence before marriage and faithfulness within restrictive monogamy - demands more than most organizations can perform. It deprives marriage of expected satisfaction while exhausting available mental forces, especially in women.
Our civilization is built upon suppression of instincts

Women are particularly harmed by civilized sexual morality. Reared under prohibition of all thought about sex and severe suppression of curiosity, they enter marriage unprepared and remain psychically infantile, often developing neuroses or finding marriage unbearable, leading to marital disasters.
The analyst must have gone through psychoanalysis himself and recognized his own complexes that would interfere with grasping patient's communications

The future of psychoanalytic therapy will increase its power through more precise understanding of transference and resistance, through the analyst's own analysis, and through increased authority once theoretical conclusions are confirmed by experience.

The child's sexual researches are driven by practical life interest, not abstract desire for knowledge. The problem of where babies come from arises from self-interested fear of losing parental love and possessions with arrival of new sibling.

The child's sexual researches fail because they approach the problem of sexuality from the wrong side - from the question of where babies come from rather than the true problem of sexual intercourse. This cognitive failure has significant consequences for sexual development.

Adults vastly underestimate children's sexual knowledge and activity. The child's apparent ignorance is often feigned - in the unconscious, the child knows much more than adults suspect, though this knowledge remains dissociated from consciousness.

The Oedipus complex - the child's sexual desires toward the parent of opposite sex and rivalry with parent of same sex - is the nuclear complex of every neurosis, the central phenomenon of human sexual life

Forgotten childhood memories are not truly forgotten but repressed. They remain active in the unconscious and determine subsequent development. What appears as innate disposition is largely the product of early childhood impressions that have been forgotten.
The sexual instinct has extraordinarily plastic quality - components can substitute for each other, exchange their objects, and one component may take over strength from others

Parapraxes (slips of tongue, pen, forgetting, bungled actions) are not chance occurrences but significant psychical acts with their own aim, expressing impulses and intentions kept back from consciousness. They demonstrate that nothing in mental life is arbitrary.

Bisexuality is not just anatomical but psychical - every human being displays both masculine and feminine mental characteristics and object-choices. Homosexuality represents dominance of one element, while heterosexuality represents dominance of the other, but both are present in everyone.

The aim of psychoanalytic treatment is not to remove every peculiarity of human character and level everyone to mediocrity, but to strengthen the ego, make it independent of the super-ego, widen its field of perception, and extend its organization so that it can appropriate fresh portions of the id

The latency period (ages 5-11) represents a developmental phase where sexual impulses undergo repression, reaction-formation (shame, disgust, morality), and sublimation. This period prepares the child for civilized life by redirecting sexual energies toward socially acceptable aims.

Puberty represents the final organization of sexuality under genital primacy, but this organization is never complete. Pregenital components persist and may emerge in foreplay or perverse sexual aims. Complete genital organization is an ideal rarely achieved.

The choice of neurosis (whether hysteria, obsessional neurosis, or other form) depends upon the point of fixation in libidinal development to which the person regresses. Hysteria corresponds to genital-incestuous fixation, while obsessional neurosis corresponds to anal-sadistic fixation.

Frustration in reality causes libido to withdraw from real objects and turn back to phantasy, reviving infantile wishes. If these infantile wishes are sufficiently strong and ego sufficiently weak, regression occurs to fixation points, producing neurotic symptoms as compromise formations.

Narcissism is an essential stage in normal development when the child takes his own body and self as love-object before turning to external objects. Narcissistic libido can be withdrawn from objects and reinvested in the self, as seen in illness, sleep, and narcissistic neuroses.
Screen memories are innocuous recollections that conceal significant childhood experiences through displacement

Symbolism in dreams, symptoms, and myths operates through universal symbolic equations (e.g., house=body, room=woman, travel=dying, riding=coitus). These symbols are archaic heritage, phylogenetically transmitted, representing primitive modes of thought expression.

The death of the father is the most important event and the most poignant loss in a man's life. It liberates the son from authority but also removes protection, forcing confrontation with own mortality. The father's death commonly precipitates neurotic illness or philosophical preoccupation.
Obsessional prohibitions and compulsive acts represent a defensive struggle against temptation and protective measures against expected misfortune

Guilt in obsessional neurosis is fully justified but displaced. The patient feels guilty not for what he has done but for his unconscious hostile wishes. The obsessional neurotic has a more sensitive moral consciousness than normal person, but this morality is at service of repression.

Religious practices and obsessional ceremonials are analogous - both involve minute prescriptions for performing acts, both involve isolation and prohibition of interruption, both arouse anxiety when neglected

Both normal and pathological mental processes are determined by same laws. The difference between health and neurosis is quantitative, not qualitative - a matter of strength of forces and success of defensive processes, not presence vs. absence of mechanisms.

Identification is primitive emotional tie with another person, preceding object-choice. The child identifies with the parent of same sex, taking parent as model. This identification becomes hostile when triangular Oedipus situation develops and child wishes to replace parent with same-sex parent.

The primal scene - observation or primal phantasy of parental intercourse - has traumatic effect on child's sexual development. Whether actually observed or phantasied, it provides schema organizing later sexual experiences and becomes focal point for understanding sexuality.

Penis envy in girls is counterpart to castration complex in boys. Upon seeing boy's genitals, girl feels herself unfairly treated, develops envy, wishes to have penis, and experiences this as narcissistic humiliation. This profoundly affects feminine development.

The therapeutic process requires the patient to repeat in transference what he cannot remember, actualizing repressed infantile impulses in relation to analyst. This repetition in present provides opportunity to work through and resolve old conflicts.

The fundamental rule of psychoanalysis requires the patient to say everything that comes to mind without selection or censorship, no matter how unimportant, embarrassing, or nonsensical it seems. This free association bypasses conscious resistance and provides access to unconscious.

Interpretation must proceed gradually, working from surface to depth. The analyst does not communicate meaning of symptom or content of unconscious until patient is within reach of it himself. Premature interpretation provokes resistance and rejection.

Working-through is the process by which patient overcomes resistance to insight already intellectually accepted. Simply knowing unconscious content is insufficient - patient must work through resistance repeatedly in multiple contexts before real change occurs.

Sublimation of sexual instinct into cultural, artistic, and intellectual achievement is civilization's primary method of dealing with sexuality. But excessive repression blocks sublimation's path, while successful sublimation requires that sexual impulses not be completely suppressed but deflected.

The myth, like the dream and symptom, represents disguised fulfillment of repressed infantile wishes. Myths are the secular dreams of youthful humanity, expressing in distorted form the deepest wishes and conflicts of the human mind.

Childhood amnesia - the forgetting of early years - results from repression of infantile sexuality. What adults cannot remember, children lived through as important sexual experiences. This infantile amnesia is precondition for subsequent neurosis.

The super-ego originates from introjection of parental authority, particularly the father, following resolution of Oedipus complex. It represents the internalized prohibitions and ideals, creating conscience and moral self-observation. Severity of super-ego may exceed actual parental strictness.

Anxiety in phobia results from transformation of libido that can find no employment. The libido withdrawn from unattainable love-object is transformed directly into anxiety, which then attaches to phobic object as means of mastering the internal danger.

The psychoanalytic situation - regular sessions, use of couch, analyst's neutrality, fundamental rule - creates special conditions promoting regression, allowing emergence of transference and providing protected space for working through infantile conflicts.

Repression creates the unconscious. What is repressed remains active, constantly striving for expression, manifesting in disguised form as symptoms, dreams, parapraxes, and derivatives. The repressed is indestructible - it never loses its cathexis or its efficacy.

Polymorphous perversity of childhood means the child is capable of every perverse sexual act, with erotogenic zones operating independently. Normal development requires these components to be brought under genital primacy, while perversion represents persistence or return to infantile organization.

The compulsion to repeat represents manifestation of repressed impulses seeking expression. Patient repeats pathological patterns in transference and life without recognizing them as repetitions. This repetition compulsion extends beyond pleasure principle.

Masturbation in childhood and puberty represents not a pathological act but normal expression of infantile and adolescent sexuality. Its repression and associated guilt can lead to neurosis, while permitting it without excessive prohibition favors healthy development.

The analyst's task is not to give advice, provide reassurance, or directly satisfy patient's needs, but to help patient understand his unconscious motivations through interpretation. The analytic stance maintains neutrality, allowing transference to develop uncontaminated.

Psychoanalysis reveals that mental life consists of continuous struggle between conflicting forces - ego instincts vs sexual instincts, consciousness vs unconscious, reality principle vs pleasure principle. Neurosis results when this conflict becomes unmanageable for the ego.

Penis envy in women originates in an early developmental phase where girls envy their brothers their sign of masculinity and feel at a disadvantage and humiliated because of the lack of it (or its diminished size) in themselves.
The 'masculine protest' in women - the wish to be masculine - represents a developmental phase closer to original narcissism than to object-love.

During the masculine phase, little girls often make no secret of their penis envy nor of the hostility towards their favoured brothers which arises from it, even attempting to urinate standing upright to prove equality.
The wish for a child in girls develops as a substitute for the wish to have a penis - the girl's libido is redirected from wanting a penis to wanting a child from the father.
The first act of intercourse can activate a woman's wish to castrate her sexual partner and keep his penis for herself, representing the return of archaic penis envy.

Behind penis envy lies women's hostile bitterness against men, which never completely disappears in the relations between the sexes and is clearly indicated in the strivings and literary productions of 'emancipated' women.
A woman's immature sexuality is discharged onto the man who first makes her acquainted with the sexual act, which accounts for the paradoxical hostile reaction to defloration.
The taboo of virginity among primitive peoples is reasonable given that it protects the future husband from the dangerous archaic reaction unleashed by defloration.

In uncommonly large numbers of cases, women remain frigid and unhappy in first marriages, whereas after dissolution they become tender wives able to make second husbands happy - the archaic hostile reaction has exhausted itself on the first object.

Defloration has not only the civilized consequence of binding the woman to the man, but also unleashes an archaic reaction of hostility toward him which can assume pathological forms and create inhibitions in married life.

Some women remain in bondage to their first husbands not through affection but because they have not completed their revenge upon them, and have not even brought the impulses for vengeance to consciousness.

In psychogenic disturbances of vision, the eyes have not only perceived changes in the external world important for self-preservation, but also qualities of objects which led to their being chosen as objects of love - their 'charms.'

Psychogenic visual disturbances occur when the sexual component instinct of looking (scopophilia) has drawn upon itself the whole of the libido, such that the ego-instincts can no longer receive their share of cathexis for the eye's function.

The ego's repression of the scopophilic sexual component instinct results in a rebellion by the ego-instincts, which refuse their function and thus produce the disturbance of vision - 'if you want to use the organ for bad sexual pleasure, you shall not use it at all.'
The paranoid forms of dementia praecox (schizophrenia) are characterized by two fundamental features: megalomania and diversion of interest from the external world (people and things).

The detachment of libido from objects without its replacement by new ones leads to megalomania - the libido that has been withdrawn from the external world is directed to the ego, producing an attitude termed narcissism.
Megalomania represents a return to an earlier stage of libidinal development in which the child's own ego was his only sexual object - a revival of infantile narcissism.

Paranoia decomposes in the same way that hysteria condenses - paranoia resolves into their elements what hysteria combines. In paranoia, internal perceptions (feelings and thought-processes) are projected outward as though they were external perceptions.

The fundamental language of paranoia transforms the formula 'I (a man) love him (a man)' through various grammatical modifications: by contradiction ('I do not love him - I hate him'), by projection ('He hates/persecutes me'), by erotic delusion ('I do not love him - I love her'), and by jealousy delusion

The persecutor in paranoia is ultimately revealed to be someone the patient once loved - the proposition 'I hate him' becomes through projection 'He hates (persecutes) me, which will justify me in hating him.'

In Schreber's case, the persecutor Flechsig was a father-substitute, and the delusion worked by transforming the proposition 'I (a man) love him (my father)' into 'I do not love him - I hate him, because HE PERSECUTES ME.'
The core conflict in paranoia is the defense against a homosexual wishful phantasy of loving a man, with the libidinal attachment having undergone fixation at the stage of narcissism.
The disposition to paranoia lies somewhere between the stages of auto-erotism, narcissism, and homosexuality, representing fixation at the narcissistic stage of development.

In Schreber's cosmology and theology, his delusional system represents an attempt at reconstruction - an attempt to recover the lost objects and re-establish libidinal relations, though in a pathological form.

Schreber's emasculation phantasy - his transformation into a woman - represents a feminine attitude toward his father (originally) and his physician (subsequently), fulfilling the repressed homosexual wish.
Schreber's splitting of his God into an upper and lower god (Ormuzd and Ahriman) mirrors the father-complex splitting into the idealized father and the hated father.
The sun in Schreber's delusional system is a sublimated father-symbol - the denial of the original human object is never completely successful, and father-symbols break through in the delusion.
The mechanism of symptom-formation in paranoia is projection - internal perceptions are suppressed and their content, after undergoing distortion, enters consciousness as external perceptions.

In normal psychological life, projection plays a role in our comprehension of other people's mental processes and our interpretations of their motivations, demonstrating that projection is not solely a pathological mechanism.

The etiology of paranoia is not exclusively homosexual - the gender of the persecutor may vary, and the specific form of paranoia (erotomaniac, persecutory, jealous) depends upon the grammatical modification of the rejected homosexual proposition.
Dreams may be used in analysis like any other day's residue, but the analyst must not attach particular importance to them and should never force their interpretation upon the patient.

Over-valuation of dreams by the analyst leads the patient into a state where he brings nothing but dreams and relies entirely on dream-life, to the neglect of dealing directly with resistances and the analytic work on waking life.
The interpretation of a dream should not be pursued unless it serves the analysis - dreams are used as vehicles for revealing unconscious material, not as ends in themselves.
The patient who makes use of his dreams as an evasion from reality and the treatment must be disabused of this tendency - dreams should aid the work, not replace it.

Transference arises spontaneously in all human relationships and in the patient's relations to the physician - it is the most powerful ally and the most formidable source of resistance in psycho-analytic treatment.

Each person develops a stereotyped method of conducting himself in sexual life (a 'psychical attitude' or 'transference pattern') through the combined operation of innate disposition and influences experienced in childhood, determining how he conducts himself in love throughout life.

If someone's need for love is not entirely satisfied by reality, he must direct his libidinal anticipatory ideas to every new person who appears, and it is highly probable that both portions of his libido (conscious and unconscious) participate in this attitude.

It is perfectly normal that the libido-cathexis of someone who is partly unsatisfied should be directed by anticipation to the person of the physician - this cathexis will attach itself to one of the 'imagos' or stereotyped patterns already present in the patient.

The physician becomes attached in the patient's mind to one of the 'imagos' of people by whom he was accustomed to be treated with affection (typically the father or mother imago), and under this assimilation the transference develops.

Transference in analysis is of two types: where it is of affectionate or friendly content that is admissible to consciousness, it becomes the vehicle of success and serves as the motive force of the joint work; but where it consists of unconscious erotic impulses, it becomes a resistance.
The struggle over transference-resistance constitutes the main work of the analysis - it is in this struggle that the patient must be convinced of the existence and power of his unconscious feelings.

The unconscious impulses do not want to be remembered as the treatment desires them to be, but endeavor to reproduce themselves in accordance with the timelessness of the unconscious and its capacity for hallucination - the patient seeks to act them out in the transference.
In severe cases, the unconscious impulses make use of the transference as their chief resistance to the treatment, transforming the most powerful ally into the greatest obstacle.
Transference is the battlefield on which all the contending forces must meet - it is in the handling of the transference that the fate of the analysis is decided.

The psycho-analyst should be opaque to his patients and, like a mirror, should show them nothing but what is shown to him - revealing nothing about himself and remaining a blank screen for projection.

The doctor should withhold all conscious influences from his capacity to attend and give himself over completely to his 'unconscious memory' - maintaining an attitude of 'evenly-suspended attention' to all that one hears.

The analyst should not direct his notice toward particular elements or make selections based on expectations or inclinations - as soon as attention is deliberately concentrated, one begins to select and follows inclination, which is precisely what must not be done.

The rule for the analyst is to be the counterpart to the fundamental rule of psycho-analysis for the patient: the patient should communicate everything without selection or omission; the analyst should catch everything with his 'evenly-suspended attention' without privileging anything.

The analyst's unconscious is able to reconstruct the patient's unconscious from the derivatives of the unconscious which are communicated to him - the analyst uses his own unconscious as an instrument to understand the patient's unconscious.

The analyst must not tolerate in himself any resistances which hold back from consciousness what has been perceived by his unconscious - if the analyst has not fully analyzed his own complexes and resistances, they will interfere with his perception of the patient's material.

Every analyst should begin his activity with a self-analysis and continually carry it deeper while making observations on his patients - anyone who fails to produce results in self-analysis should recognize his unfitness to treat patients by analysis.
The analyst should not take notes during sessions, as selection of material for notation interferes with evenly-suspended attention and introduces a disturbing element into the relationship.
The analyst must not attempt to remember particular material or fix his expectation on particular outcomes - memory works best when it functions spontaneously rather than being deliberately strained.

The analyst should not engage in scientific investigation during treatment - attempts to understand theoretically during the session interfere with therapeutic listening and introduce counter-transference elements.
No analyst can take a patient further than he has gone himself in his own analysis - the analyst's unresolved conflicts set limits to what he can accomplish with patients.
The analyst should avoid therapeutic ambition - the need to achieve cures or produce impressive results introduces personal motives that interfere with neutral analytic work.

Anyone who wishes to carry out analyses must conduct himself as emotionlessly as a surgeon performing an operation - the surgeon puts aside all his feelings including his human sympathy while focusing on the single aim of performing the operation as skillfully as possible.
Patients repeat in the transference all unwanted occurrences and painful emotions rather than remembering them as something belonging to the past - this is the essence of 'acting out' or 'agieren.'
The greater the resistance, the more extensively will acting out (repetition) replace remembering - in the most extreme cases, the patient does not remember anything at all but 'acts out' everything.

The patient reproduces material not as a memory but as an action - he repeats it without knowing that he is repeating it, demonstrating that the repressed seeks to be reproduced in present experience rather than remembered as past.

The transference creates an intermediate region between illness and real life through which the transition from one to the other is made - the transference is a piece of real experience but artificially constructed with provisional character.

The main instrument for curbing the patient's compulsion to repeat and transforming it into a motive for remembering is the handling of the transference - allowing repetition to unfold in the transference under controlled conditions permits analytic work on it.
Working-through the resistances is the part of the work that effects the greatest changes in the patient and distinguishes analytic treatment from any kind of treatment by suggestion.

Even after the patient has recognized a resistance and its interpretation, he must work through it - overcome it by continuing the analytic work under its dominance until it has been gradually exhausted.

The working-through of resistances is in practice an arduous task and a trial of patience for the patient and analyst alike, yet it is the part of the work that brings about the most enduring changes.

When the analyst perceives that the patient is experiencing an intense feeling of love for himself in the transference, this transference-love should neither be gratified nor suppressed, but should be handled as something unreal - an inevitable transference phenomenon to be traced back to its unconscious sources

The patient's falling in love with the analyst is induced by the analytic situation and is not to be attributed to the charms of the analyst's own person - it has the character of a compulsion deriving from the patient's infantile fixations.

The patient's love in the transference is genuine and not less real for being transference - it has most of the qualities of genuine falling in love, though it is determined by infantile prototypes and lacks concern for reality.

The analyst must not yield to the patient's demands for love gratification, but equally must not brutally rebuff or express contempt for the patient's feelings - the analytic situation demands that both abstinence and respect be maintained.

If the analyst yielded to the patient's demands for love, it would be a victory for the patient but a complete defeat for the treatment - the analyst would have repeated the patient's infantile pattern without enabling any real insight or change.

The analyst's task is to keep the patient's transference-love in check and use it analytically - to show the patient that this love is determined by infantile fixations and to help trace it back to its unconscious roots.

The psychical apparatus is governed first by the pleasure principle - the automatic regulation by feelings belonging to the pleasure-unpleasure series, with unpleasure relating to an increase in excitation and pleasure to a diminution.

The pleasure principle proves inefficacious for the ego's self-preservation in the external world, as it seeks immediate gratification without regard for reality - a state of merely wishing cannot be sustained, as needs persist and become urgent.

The reality principle represents a modification of the pleasure principle - what is presented in the mind is no longer what is agreeable but what is real, even if it should be disagreeable, securing eventual pleasure through detour rather than immediate gratification.

With the introduction of the reality principle, one species of thought-activity was split off - phantasy remains dominated by the pleasure principle alone and continues seeking immediate wish-fulfillment free from reality-testing.

The replacement of the pleasure principle by the reality principle brings about a series of adaptations: development of attention, notation and memory, judgment as reality-testing, thought as experimental action, and motor discharge delayed for purposive action.

The supersession of the pleasure principle by the reality principle is not sudden or universal but affects different mental impulses to differing degrees - the sexual instincts remain governed by the pleasure principle for much longer.

Education can be described as an incitement to the conquest of the pleasure principle and its replacement by the reality principle - it seeks the individual's benefit and accelerates a developmental transition that would otherwise occur spontaneously.

Art represents a reconciliation of the two principles in a unique way - the artist turns from reality toward phantasy, but finds a way back by shaping phantasies into new realities that gain social value.

The replacement of the pleasure principle by the reality principle does not dethrone the former but only safeguards it - a momentary pleasure with uncertain results is given up, but only to gain a later assured pleasure through regard for reality.
Neurosis onset can occur through frustration - when reality refuses satisfaction of sexual needs, driving the libido to regressive paths of satisfaction and symptom-formation.

Neurosis can onset following developmental changes requiring increased libidinal demands beyond the person's capacity (as at puberty, menopause, or at critical life transitions), representing onset through excess demand.
Neurosis onset through inhibition of development occurs when the subject remains arrested at an earlier stage of psychosexual development and cannot advance to more mature forms of satisfaction.
Traumatic neuroses onset when a single powerful experience overwhelms the ego's capacity for mastery, breaking through stimulus protection and creating lasting disturbance.

The common factor in all types of neurosis onset is the inability of the ego to master the quantity of excitation confronting it, whether from external frustration, developmental demands, fixation, or trauma.
The disposition to obsessional neurosis lies in a pre-genital organization of the libido, in which sadism and anal erotism play the principal parts.
In obsessional neurosis, there has been a regression from the genital stage to the earlier sadistic-anal stage, transforming loving impulses into hostile ones and sexual aims into destructive ones.

The chronological sequence of libidinal development (oral, sadistic-anal, genital) suggests that obsessional neurosis requires fixation to have occurred at the sadistic-anal stage before the genital organization was reached.

The ambivalence characteristic of obsessional neurosis originates in the sadistic-anal phase where love and hate, tenderness and aggressivity, are not yet differentiated and coexist in the same impulse.

The temporal relation between the onset of the ego's repressive activity and the level of libidinal organization determines the choice of neurosis - premature ego development relative to libido development predisposes to obsessional neurosis.
In savage races, the first system of human thought (animism) assumes that everything in nature is animate like the self and populated by spirits - the world is conceived on the model of the ego.

Animism represents a psychological system organizing not only natural phenomena but also the technique for dealing with them - through magic, which assumes that physical processes follow the laws of mental life.

Magic operates by two principles: the law of similarity (like produces like, effects resemble causes) and the law of contact or contagion (things once in contact continue to act on each other at a distance).
The omnipotence of thoughts is the primitive belief that wishes and thoughts can directly alter reality - the overvaluation of mental acts as if they were equivalent to real acts.

The omnipotence of thoughts persists in obsessional neurosis, where patients believe their hostile wishes can cause real harm and must be undone by compulsive rituals - demonstrating that this archaic mode returns in neurosis.

The development of human world-views follows three stages: the animistic (mythological), the religious, and the scientific, corresponding to the stages of libidinal development - narcissistic, object-finding, and maturity.
The taboo is the oldest form of human moral restriction, predating religion and having two opposed meanings: sacred/consecrated and uncanny/dangerous/forbidden/unclean.

Taboo prohibitions are different from religious or moral prohibitions - they have no foundation in divine command but impose their own authority, with violation producing automatic punishment through internal necessity.

The most ancient and important taboo prohibitions are the two fundamental laws of totemism: not to kill the totem animal and to avoid sexual intercourse with members of the totem clan of the opposite sex.

The exogamy connected with the totem represents the most drastic measure preventing incest that could possibly have been devised - it prevents not only sexual intercourse with mother and sisters but with all female members of the clan.
The incest taboo must have originated from a powerful incestuous desire - what is not desired does not need to be forbidden with such intensity and universality.
The ambivalence toward the tabooed object is fundamental - the taboo person or thing is simultaneously desired and feared, attractive and dangerous, generating opposed emotional attitudes.

Taboo observances in primitive peoples are remarkably similar to obsessional symptoms in neurotics - both involve prohibitions, renunciations, isolation, ceremonials, and the fear that violation will be magically punished.
The psychological basis of taboo is ambivalent emotional attitudes - every taboo conceals a desire, and the prohibition protects against acting on the unconscious wish.

The treatment of enemies in primitive cultures reveals that they are simultaneously feared and revered - the taboos surrounding conquered enemies show that the victor both desires to harm and fears retaliation.

Rulers are subject to elaborate taboos because their subjects harbor both veneration and hostile impulses toward them - the taboo protects the ruler but also restricts him, expressing the ambivalence of the subject's attitude.
The taboo of the dead arises from ambivalence - survivors both mourn and harbor hostile feelings toward the deceased, and project these hostile wishes onto the ghost or spirit, which is then feared.
Conscience originates from ambivalence toward loved persons - the need to restrict hostile impulses toward those we love forms the basis of moral conscience and taboo observance.
The totem animal is a substitute for the father - totemism represents an early form of father-worship where the father's authority is projected onto an animal ancestor.

The origin of totemism lies in the primal crime - in the remote past, the primal father was killed and eaten by his sons, who banded together against the father's monopoly over women and his tyrannical rule.
After the parricide, the sons experienced remorse and guilt - they both hated the father who stood as an obstacle to their power and sexual wishes, but also loved and admired him.

The taboo against killing the totem (father-substitute) and the prohibition of incest (renunciation of the women) represent deferred obedience to the father - the sons grant to the father in death the authority they had fought against in life.

The totem meal, in which the totem animal is ceremonially killed and eaten by all clan members, represents a repetition and commemoration of the original parricide - a reenactment of the primal crime.

By eating the father (totem animal), the sons achieve identification with him and acquire a portion of his strength - the totemic system is based on preserving the memory of the father through periodic renewal of the crime.

Religion originates in the son's guilt over parricide - the totem animal is replaced by a god, and the son's ambivalence finds expression in the alternation of defiance and submission toward the deity.

The Christian communion, in which believers consume the body and blood of Christ, represents the direct heir of the totem meal - it repeats the incorporation of the father-god to achieve union with him.

Social organization originates in the brothers' renunciation of the women they had liberated by killing the father - to prevent fighting among themselves, they established exogamy and restricted each other's access to incestuous objects.
The sense of guilt arising from the primal parricide has been inherited through phylogeny and persists in humanity's unconscious - it forms the basis of religion, morality, and social organization.

The Oedipus complex is the nucleus of neurosis because it recapitulates humanity's primal experience - the child's wishes to kill the father and possess the mother repeat the original crime that founded human civilization.
Children's animal phobias represent a displacement of fear and ambivalence from the father onto an animal substitute - the phobic animal is always a father-surrogate.

The development of culture rests on restrictions placed on instinctual satisfaction - the renunciations imposed by totemism (no parricide, no incest) form the foundation of all subsequent moral and social development.
Psycho-analysis has demonstrated that the first impulses of a child are incestuous and that such wishes persist in the unconscious throughout life, forming the nucleus of later neurotic conflict.

The individual's emotional attitude toward the totem recapitulates the child's emotional attitude toward the father - the ambivalence, fear, and veneration directed toward the totem mirror the Oedipus complex.

In the theme of the three caskets (Merchant of Venice, King Lear, Judgment of Paris), the choice among three women represents the choice among three essential forms of woman in man's life: the mother who bears him, the beloved who is his equal, and death who receives him.

The third casket (lead) represents death - it is chosen because it symbolizes silence, pallor, and muteness, all attributes of death. The reversal in the myths (choosing the 'best' rather than 'death') represents wish-fulfillment against the reality of mortality.
The three Fates (Moirae) - Clotho who spins the thread of life, Lachesis who measures it, and Atropos who cuts it - represent the three aspects of the mother: creator, maintainer, and destroyer.

The Goddess of Death in mythology is derived from the Goddess of Love - the Greeks' Aphrodite and Romans' Venus originally possessed attributes of death deities, showing the connection between love and death.

Man's relationship with the three women recapitulates his relationship with the mother throughout life - she is the woman who bears him (mother), the woman who loves him (beloved replacing the mother), and Mother Earth who receives him in death.

The transformation in myths from terrifying Death to desirable Love represents the operation of wish-fulfillment - the myth replaces what we fear (death) with what we desire (love), allowing us to contemplate mortality.

Fausse reconnaissance ('déjà raconté') - the feeling of having already told something that one is currently relating - represents a compromise formation between the impulse to tell something important from the past and the resistance against revealing it.

The 'déjà raconté' experience allows the person to enjoy the satisfaction of having revealed the important material (as though it had been told) while maintaining the repression (since it actually remains untold).

The Moses of Michelangelo represents Moses after his return from Sinai, in the moment of checking his anger at seeing the people worshiping the golden calf - the statue captures the instant of controlling intense affect.

Michelangelo modified the traditional Moses by depicting him restraining his anger rather than giving way to it - the statue shows a Moses who has overcome passion in favor of duty, representing the artist's own psychological conflict.

The meaning of great works of art can be discovered through minute observation of small details and features - trivial details often betray the creator's unconscious intentions more clearly than obvious features.
Art works affect us powerfully by arousing the same emotional state in us that existed in the artist during creation - we reconstruct the artist's psychological process from studying the work itself.
Dreams commonly incorporate material from fairy tales and myths, which serve as collective repositories of typical human experiences and unconscious phantasies shared across cultures.
Fairy tales and myths provide ready-made symbolic expressions for unconscious phantasies - the dreamer borrows from this cultural storehouse to express personal unconscious material.
The recurrence of the same themes in fairy tales across different cultures demonstrates that these tales express universal unconscious phantasies and typical human experiences.

Children's lies can serve defensive purposes - the child may lie to protect himself from punishment or to deny painful reality, and such lies should be understood as defensive operations rather than simple moral failures.
Some children's lies represent phantasy formations that have broken through into consciousness and been asserted as reality - the child confuses wish-fulfillment phantasy with actual events.
Overly harsh moral demands and punishment for lying may intensify rather than cure the tendency to lie - the child needs understanding of the phantasy behind the lie rather than pure condemnation.

In masturbation, both physical and psychological factors play roles - the act may serve to discharge sexual tension but also represents phantasy fulfillment and may become a vehicle for expressing unconscious wishes.
The harm in masturbation lies not in the physical act itself but in the excessive sense of guilt it produces, which may interfere with later sexual development and contribute to neurotic disposition.
Psycho-analysis claims interest from philosophy because it compels philosophy to take account of unconscious mental processes - any theory of mind that neglects the unconscious is inadequate.

For philology and the study of language, psycho-analysis reveals that linguistic symbols and expressions often preserve ancient meanings connected to the body and sexual functions, with symbolism being rooted in unconscious equation of disparate objects.

Psycho-analysis has interest for biology in demonstrating the fundamental bisexuality of human beings - both physical and psychological bisexual tendencies are present and influence sexual development and object-choice.

For the history of civilization, psycho-analysis shows that the development of culture depends upon restriction of instinctual satisfaction - cultural progress requires instinctual renunciation and sublimation.

In the study of religion, psycho-analysis demonstrates that religious beliefs and practices derive from the same sources as neurotic symptoms - both represent attempts to master infantile conflicts, particularly those relating to the father.

Psycho-analysis shows that mythology and folklore preserve collective unconscious phantasies - myths represent disguised wish-fulfillments of whole peoples, just as dreams represent wish-fulfillments of individuals.

For aesthetics, psycho-analysis reveals that artistic creation involves regression to primary process thinking combined with masterful form - the artist reconciles infantile pleasure sources with mature technique.

In education, psycho-analysis shows that early childhood experiences have lasting effects on character formation - education should aim at optimal management of instinctual forces rather than mere suppression.
Psycho-analysis demonstrates to sociology that individual psychology and group psychology are fundamentally connected - social institutions arise from attempts to solve common psychological problems.

For jurisprudence, psycho-analysis shows that the concept of responsibility requires consideration of unconscious motivation - legal responsibility cannot be determined without understanding the unconscious forces behind actions.
In psychiatry, psycho-analysis has shown that mental disorders previously thought meaningless have psychological meaning - every symptom serves a purpose in the patient's mental economy.
The position in which a person wakes from a dream often relates to the content of the dream and may represent a bodily expression of what was dreamed.

Self-criticism by neurotics often represents an internalized critical voice (superego precursor) directed against forbidden instinctual wishes - the patient attacks himself to avoid punishment from outside.
Dreams may condense or expand the representation of time - years may be represented as moments or moments as extended periods, reflecting the timelessness of unconscious processes.

Two rooms in a dream often represent the two openings of the female body (mouth and genitals) or the transformation from 'two' (breasts, buttocks) to 'one' (genitals), expressing sexual symbolism through spatial representation.
Fragmentary dreams that seem incomplete often defend against disturbing material by breaking off the dream narrative before reaching the anxiety-producing conclusion.
Dreams about dead people often fulfill wishes about their death or express guilt over having wished for their death - the dreamer's relationship with the deceased is re-experienced in the dream.

When symptoms of the illness appear in the dream, this often indicates that the symptoms are being used as day-residues to express unconscious wish-fulfillment - the symptom becomes material for dream-work.
Overcoats in dreams typically symbolize condoms - the dream expresses sexual wishes or anxieties about sexual intercourse through the overcoat representation.
Shoes in dreams commonly represent the female genitals - dirty, torn, or disgraced shoes (feet) express devaluation or disgust toward sexuality.

The representation of ages in dreams often condenses different time periods - a person may appear simultaneously at different ages, or one person's age may represent another's, expressing temporal displacement.
Dreams with an unrecognized precipitating cause often conceal distressing current events that the dreamer wishes to deny - the manifest dream obscures its connection to recent trauma.

In folklore dreams, particularly those about bodily functions and sexuality, the dream-symbolism reveals unconscious equations between disparate bodily products and sexual elements that are shared across cultures.
Penis symbolism appears commonly in folklore dreams through representations of elongated objects, tools, and weapons - the symbolic equation is evident across different cultural traditions.
Faeces symbolism in dreams and folklore equates excrement with gold, money, and gifts - the unconscious preserves the infantile equation between bodily products and valuable possessions.
Dreams about finding treasure typically represent wish-fulfillments related to anal erotism and the discovery of one's own body - the treasure symbolizes valuable bodily products or sexual organs.
The ring in dreams and folklore commonly symbolizes the female genitals - stories about magic rings or rings of fidelity express unconscious phantasies about female sexuality.

Educational experiences in adolescence (particularly at gymnasium/secondary school) leave lasting impressions because they occur during a time of heightened emotional receptivity and when the personality is being formed.
Teachers inevitably serve as father-substitutes for their students - the student's emotional relationship with teachers recapitulates and is determined by his relationship with his father.

Students transfer onto their teachers the ambivalent feelings they harbor toward their fathers - they both admire and rebel against teachers with the same ambivalence that characterizes the father-son relationship.

The liberation from parental authority is one of the most necessary but also most painful achievements of development - education aids this process by providing other authority figures (teachers) through whom the conflict with the father can be partially worked through.
Former students' idealization of certain teachers and scorn for others reflects not the objective merits of these teachers but the students' own emotional needs and conflicts projected onto them.

The significant psychological influence of teachers derives not from their knowledge but from their personalities - students are affected by the teacher as a person rather than by the subject matter taught.

School experiences gain their significance from the fact that they represent the student's first major encounter with social organization outside the family - the school is the training ground for adult social life.

Students' ambivalent feelings toward their teachers protect them from being overwhelmed by exclusive attachment to their fathers - the distribution of ambivalence across multiple authority figures is developmentally beneficial.

The psycho-analytic view of psychogenic disturbance demonstrates that conversion symptoms occur when the ego-instincts are overwhelmed by sexual instincts - the organ 'struck with repression' becomes unable to fulfill its ego-function.

The selection of the organ for conversion symptom is not arbitrary but determined by the specific role that organ plays in both ego-preservation and sexual gratification - the organ must serve both instinctual groups.

The relation of the eye to objects combines both functions - perception for self-preservation and scopophilic sexual pleasure - which is why it becomes a site for conversion symptoms when these functions conflict.

In Schreber's delusional system, his transformation into God's wife and the subsequent redemption of the world through bearing divine offspring represents the ultimate fulfillment of his feminine homosexual wish toward his father, sublimated into religious-cosmic significance.

The voices (Stimmenhören) experienced in paranoia and related conditions represent the auditory perception of thoughts - what should remain internal mental processes break through into consciousness as external voices.

Schreber's concept of 'soul murder' (Seelenmord) represents his unconscious perception of the psychological danger posed by submission to homosexual wishes - the fear that yielding to these wishes would destroy his masculine identity.

The successful adaptation to reality in paranoia's reconstruction phase should not be mistaken for recovery - the delusional system represents a new pathological equilibrium rather than restoration of normal functioning.
