Anxiety (Angst) constitutes the fundamental problem of the neuroses, the nodal point at which the most various and important questions converge, and a riddle whose solution would cast a flood of light upon our whole mental existence

Three types of anxiety must be distinguished: realistic anxiety (normal fear of external dangers), neurotic anxiety (fear disproportionate to actual danger), and moral anxiety (conscience or superego anxiety)

Realistic anxiety appears entirely rational and intelligible, representing a reaction to the perception of an external danger - an injury that is expected and foreseen; it is connected with the flight reflex and may be regarded as an expression of the self-preservative instinct

Anxiety prepares the organism for danger by heightening sensory attention and motor tension; the anxiety-affect consists of motor discharge (trembling, perspiration, palpitations) and sensations of unpleasure

Neurotic anxiety manifests in three forms: free-floating general apprehensiveness (expectant anxiety), anxiety attached to specific phobic objects or situations, and anxiety in hysteria and other neuroses appearing without apparent connection to danger

In anxiety neurosis, libido is turned into anxiety when denied normal discharge: the anxiety represents transformed libido which has not been employed psychically but discharged in the form of anxiety

Phobic anxiety differs from expectant anxiety by being attached to specific objects or situations, but shares with it the characteristic of anxiety disproportionate to actual danger; the phobic object serves as a condition under which anxiety is permitted release

The ego creates the phobia as an attempt to escape from the libidinal demand made by the id; the phobic avoidance protects the ego from experiencing anxiety by avoiding the situation that would provoke the forbidden libidinal impulse

Anxiety in hysteria and obsessional neurosis accompanies symptoms: the anxiety is the quota of affect that has become liberated through the process of repression and which would otherwise have been employed in some other way if it had not been repressed

The transformation of libido into anxiety occurs through two mechanisms: direct transformation when libido cannot be discharged (anxiety neurosis), and liberation of affect quota when repression occurs (hysteria and obsessional neurosis)

The equation 'repression = anxiety' is fundamentally correct: repression arises from the ego's anxiety-readiness, and the repressed libidinal impulse is transformed into the anxiety which accompanies neurotic symptoms

The right to separate ego-instincts from sexual instincts cannot be shaken: it is implied in the existence of sexual life as a distinct activity of the individual, though the depth and importance of this separation must be determined by observing how differently the two behave

If hunger and thirst (self-preservative instincts) are unsatisfied, the result is never their transformation into anxiety, whereas the changing of unsatisfied libido into anxiety is among the best known and most frequently observed of phenomena - demonstrating a fundamental difference between ego and sexual instincts

Libido is the energy of the sexual instincts directed to an object; it is qualitatively distinct from the energy of the ego-instincts and is capable of transformations, displacements, and regressions not observed in self-preservative impulses
Narcissism is the libidinal complement to egoism of the self-preservative instinct: it is the libidinal cathexis of the ego, representing a state in which the ego itself is taken as the love-object

Primary narcissism is the original state of earliest childhood before any object-love develops; the infant's libido is entirely self-directed, and only gradually does libido extend to external objects while retaining the ego as a reservoir

The distribution of libido follows a hydraulic model: the more libido is employed in object-cathexes, the more it is withdrawn from the ego, and vice versa; object-love impoverishes the ego, while narcissistic withdrawal enriches it
Secondary narcissism occurs when object-libido is withdrawn back to the ego, as in states of sleep, organic illness, hypochondria, and the narcissistic neuroses (schizophrenia, paranoia, melancholia)

The narcissistic neuroses (dementia praecox, paranoia, melancholia) are characterized by withdrawal of libido from objects and the external world; this makes them largely inaccessible to psychoanalytic influence, since transference cannot be established where no object-cathexis exists

Megalomania in paranoia and schizophrenia results from the cathexis of the ego with libido withdrawn from objects; the ego swells with the influx of narcissistic libido, producing grandiose delusions and omnipotent fantasies

The ego-ideal is a substitute for the lost narcissism of childhood; what the individual projects before him as his ideal is the substitute for the narcissistic perfection he enjoyed as a child, attempting to recover the perfection attributed to his earlier state

Object-choice can follow either the narcissistic type (loving what one is, was, or would like to be) or the anaclitic/attachment type (loving those who satisfy self-preservative needs, modeled on parents); narcissistic choice predominates in homosexuality and in certain forms of love

Transference is the fundamental phenomenon that makes psychoanalytic therapy possible: patients develop intense emotional attitudes toward the analyst - love, hate, dependency - which are repetitions of attitudes toward important figures from childhood, particularly parents

Transference is not created by analysis but merely uncovered by it; it arises spontaneously in all human relationships and is particularly intense in neurotics, whose capacity for object-love has been impaired by fixation to infantile objects

Positive transference (affectionate feelings toward the analyst) can be divided into conscious friendly feelings, which are unobjectionable and maintain the therapeutic alliance, and unconscious erotic feelings, which become resistance when they push for gratification rather than understanding

Negative transference (hostile feelings toward the analyst) and the erotic component of positive transference constitute the transference-resistance: they obstruct the work by demanding emotional gratification instead of intellectual understanding and remembering

The transference-neurosis replaces the patient's ordinary neurosis: the symptoms are re-created in the relationship with the analyst, transforming the neurosis into a transference phenomenon that can be directly observed and analyzed in the present

Transference creates an intermediate realm between illness and real life through which the transition from one to the other is made; the new condition (transference-neurosis) has taken over all features of the illness but represents an artificial illness that is accessible to intervention at every point

The handling of transference is the most difficult but also the most important part of analytic technique: overcoming transference-resistances accomplishes the removal of repressions and alters the economic conditions, making cure possible

Transference manifestations differ across neurotic structures: hysterics rapidly form intense erotic transferences; obsessionals maintain negative transference and ambivalence; narcissistic neuroses fail to develop transference, making them unsuitable for standard analytic treatment

Direct suggestion aims at suppressing symptoms by authority without investigating their motives; psycho-analysis aims at uncovering and removing the motives for illness, relying on the patient's understanding rather than the physician's authority

Hypnotic and suggestive therapy, though rapid and superficially effective, provides only temporary symptomatic relief; symptoms return because the underlying conflicts remain unresolved, and the patient remains dependent on the physician's authority

Psycho-analytic treatment makes far greater demands on the patient and the physician than suggestive therapy: it requires the patient's active intellectual participation and the physician's understanding of unconscious processes, and it is lengthy, laborious, and often unpleasant

Psycho-analysis cannot alter hereditary disposition or undo childhood experiences; it can only address the third factor in neurotic causation - real frustration in adult life - by helping the patient redistribute libido more advantageously and overcome internal obstacles to satisfaction

The therapeutic work of analysis consists in overcoming internal resistances: the ego must learn to tolerate previously repressed impulses, integrate them into consciousness, and achieve better compromise-solutions than repression and symptom-formation

Analysis helps the ego in three ways: by increasing its knowledge of the unconscious (making the unconscious conscious), by accustoming it gradually to tolerate repressed material (overcoming resistance), and by providing it with more energy by reducing expenditure on maintaining repressions

The formula 'making the unconscious conscious' must be understood economically, not merely topographically: it means altering the distribution of psychic energy by lifting repressions, not simply bringing unconscious content into awareness intellectually

Intellectual knowledge alone accomplishes nothing: the patient may acknowledge unconscious material intellectually while maintaining emotional resistance; cure requires overcoming affective resistances and achieving economic redistribution of libido

Analysis operates through the lever of transference: by analyzing transference-resistance, the analyst helps the patient recognize and overcome the same patterns of resistance that maintain the neurosis, achieving alteration at the economic level

The gain from illness (Krankheitsgewinn) creates a major obstacle to treatment: neurotic symptoms provide real advantages - avoiding responsibilities, gaining sympathy, maintaining a dependent position - which the patient unconsciously wishes to preserve despite conscious complaints

Primary gain from illness is the advantage of escaping from internal conflict through symptom-formation; secondary gain comprises all external advantages subsequently accruing from being ill - sympathy, reduced expectations, compensation, relief from duties

When secondary gain from illness is considerable and no real substitute for it is available, the chances of influencing the neurosis by treatment must be reckoned very low; external circumstances may make neurosis the only tolerable solution

The physician must sometimes admit that neurosis represents the most harmless and socially tolerable solution to an insoluble life-situation; not all suffering can or should be removed, and the analyst must recognize when neurosis serves a protective function

Successful analysis requires optimal conditions: not too old (plasticity decreases after fifty), not too young (children lack necessary reflective capacity), sufficient intelligence, moderate severity of illness (severe cases exhausted by symptoms), stable external circumstances, and adequate time and resources

Psycho-analysis effects permanent alteration in the economic distribution of psychic forces, producing lasting changes that protect against relapse; unlike suggestion, which remains foreign to the ego, analytic cure integrates previously repressed material into the ego's organization

Analysis employs suggestion only in a preliminary way to motivate the patient to work; the essential therapeutic action comes from the patient's own efforts in overcoming resistances, not from the analyst's authority or suggestions

The accusation that psycho-analytic findings are artifacts of suggestion is refuted by three facts: analyses produce uniform findings across different analysts and patients, patients regularly resist rather than accept suggestions, and the same unconscious mechanisms are found in non-therapeutic contexts (dreams, parapraxes, folklore)

Patients who complain most loudly about their illness often offer the most resistance to treatment; this paradox reveals the unconscious secondary gains and conflicting motivations that maintain the neurosis despite conscious suffering

Every neurotic symptom, once established, acquires a secondary function as it becomes integrated into the personality: it establishes a modus vivendi with other mental systems, becomes useful for new purposes, and develops a self-preservative tendency resisting removal

The ego is not a trustworthy or impartial agency in judging the neurosis: it is the very power that has created repressions and maintains them, so accepting the ego's account would mean judging the dispute by the victorious party, inevitably leading to error

Traumatic neuroses, particularly war neuroses, demonstrate a self-interested motive on the part of the ego seeking protection and advantage: the ego assents to the illness and maintains it when recovery would expose it again to the dangers that precipitated the neurosis

The ego makes a bad bargain by accepting the neurosis: though it gains relief from conflict and obtains secondary advantages, it pays too dearly through the suffering attached to symptoms, which often exceed the original conflict's torments

The narcissistic neuroses (dementia praecox, paranoia, melancholia) demonstrate that the ego can become the object of libidinal cathexis: in these conditions, libido withdrawn from the external world and objects is redirected to the ego itself, producing megalomania and loss of reality-testing

Sleep represents a temporary return to primary narcissism: the sleeper withdraws libidinal cathexes from objects and the external world, concentrating them on the wish to sleep; this narcissistic withdrawal accounts for the hallucinatory character of dreams and the sleeper's indifference to reality

Physical illness causes a withdrawal of libido from objects back to the ego (hypochondriacal cathexis of the affected organ); during illness, the patient becomes narcissistic, withdraws interest from the external world, ceases to love, and concentrates on bodily sensations

Megalomania is not a new creation but an exaggeration of a state that already existed: it represents magnification of the infantile narcissistic state, to which the patient regresses by withdrawing libidinal cathexes from objects and reattaching them to the ego

Being in love involves a flowing-over of ego-libido onto the object: the object is treated as equivalent to one's own ego, impoverishing the ego in favor of the object; at the height of infatuation, the object has consumed the ego, producing a state of devotion and self-sacrifice

Transference occurs not only in psycho-analysis but in all human relationships: doctors, teachers, and authorities of all kinds regularly receive transferences, and much of their success depends on the positive transferences directed toward them by patients, students, or followers

Unanalyzed transferences in non-analytic relationships exert unrecognized influence: the patient's compliance with the doctor's orders, the student's admiration of the teacher, the believer's faith in religious leaders all depend on unconscious transferences that remain unexamined

The unique feature of psycho-analytic technique is that transference, which elsewhere operates unconsciously and unexamined, is deliberately made conscious, analyzed, and used as a therapeutic instrument; what in other treatments is a source of suggestion becomes in analysis the subject of investigation

I once knew two twin brothers, both of whom were endowed with strong libidinal impulses

The other went the same way at first, but it became unpleasant for him to be trespassing on his brother’s preserves, and, owing to the likeness between them, to be mistaken for him on intimate occasions; so he got out of the difficulty by becoming homosexual

Another time I treated a youngish man, an artist, unmistakably bisexual in disposition, in whom the homosexual trend had come to the fore simultaneously with a disturbance in his work
He fled from both women and work together
The analysis, which was able to bring him back to both, showed that fear of his father was the most powerful psychical motive for both the disturbances, which were really renunciations
